# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1882-louisville-eclipse-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th century's version of the **Baltimore Orioles** were founded in 1882 as part of the new American Association.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] Owned by wealthy Harry Von der Horst, the Orioles finished the season in last place with only 19 wins.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-boston-red-caps-season] The **1882 Boston Red Caps season** was the 12th season of the franchise.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps were a team in transition, as co-founder and longtime manager Harry Wright left the team and was replaced by John Morrill.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1882 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 45–39 record, good for third place in the National League.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Blues finished the 1882 season at 42–40, fifth place in the National League.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1882 Detroit Wolverines** finished the season with a 42–41 record, good for fifth place in the National League.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-detroit-wolverines-season] During the season, Detroit owner William G.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-detroit-wolverines-season] Thompson had a private investigator look into umpire Richard Higham, after suspicions of matchfixing, which resulted in Higham becoming the only umpire to be banned in MLB history.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1882 Louisville Eclipse season** was the first season as a Major League club for the franchise.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The team, which had played for several years as a semi-pro team, joined the new American Association league.
[src:1882-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] They finished the season with a 42–38 record, good for third place.
